{"text": "In a historical experiment to determine Planck's constant, a metal surface was irradiated with light of different wavelengths. The emitted photoelectron energies were measured by applying a stopping potential. The relevant data for the wavelength ($\lambda$) and the corresponding stopping potential ($V_0$) are given below:

$$\begin{array}{|c|c|} \hline \lambda (\mu\text{m}) & V_0 (\text{Volt}) \\ \hline 0.3 & 2.0 \\ \hline 0.4 & 1.0 \\ \hline 0.5 & 0.4 \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Given that $c = 3 \times 10^8 \text{ ms}^{-1}$ and $e = 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \text{ C}$, Planck's constant (in units of J-s) found from such an experiment is:", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "The major product of the following reaction sequence is:

$$\text{}$$

Choose the correct option from the following:", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1VAFMBNVdLfgXf1n0WSFK-kW-RS_85R3v=w1200"}

{"text": "A charged particle (electron or proton) is introduced at the origin $(x = 0, y = 0, z = 0)$ with a given initial velocity $\vec{v}$. A uniform electric field $\vec{E}$ and magnetic field $\vec{B}$ are given in columns 1, 2 and 3, respectively. The quantities $E_0, B_0$ are positive in magnitude.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|} \hline \textbf{Column I} & \textbf{Column 2} & \textbf{Column 3} \\ \hline (\text{I}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (i) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{z} & (P) \vec{B} = -B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{II}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = \frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{y} & (ii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{y} & (Q) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{III}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 0 & (iii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{x} & (R) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{y} \\ \hline (\text{IV}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (iv) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{x} & (S) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{z} \\ \hline \end{array}$$

In which case would the particle move in a straight line along the negative direction of $y$-axis (i.e., move along $-\hat{y}$)?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "A charged particle (electron or proton) is introduced at the origin $(x = 0, y = 0, z = 0)$ with a given initial velocity $\vec{v}$. A uniform electric field $\vec{E}$ and magnetic field $\vec{B}$ are given in columns 1, 2 and 3, respectively. The quantities $E_0, B_0$ are positive in magnitude.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|} \hline \textbf{Column I} & \textbf{Column 2} & \textbf{Column 3} \\ \hline (\text{I}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (i) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{z} & (P) \vec{B} = -B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{II}) \text{ Electron with } \vec{v} = \frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{y} & (ii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{y} & (Q) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{x} \\ \hline (\text{III}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 0 & (iii) \vec{E} = -E_0 \hat{x} & (R) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{y} \\ \hline (\text{IV}) \text{ Proton with } \vec{v} = 2\frac{E_0}{B_0}\hat{x} & (iv) \vec{E} = E_0 \hat{x} & (S) \vec{B} = B_0 \hat{z} \\ \hline \end{array}$$
In which case will the particle move in a straight line with constant velocity?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "An organic acid $\text{P}$ $(\text{C}_{11}\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_2)$ can easily be oxidized to a dibasic acid which reacts with ethylene glycol to produce a polymer Dacron. Upon ozonolysis, $\text{P}$ gives an aliphatic ketone as one of the products. $\text{P}$ undergoes the following reaction sequences to furnish $\text{R}$ via $\text{Q}$. The compound $\text{P}$ also undergoes another set of reactions to produce $\text{S}$.

$$\text{S} \xleftarrow[\text{5) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C}]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{NH}_3/\Delta \\ \text{3) } \text{Br}_2/\text{NaOH} \\ \text{4) } \text{CHCl}_3, \text{ KOH}, \Delta \end{matrix}} \text{P} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{NaBH}_4]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{SOCl}_2 \\ \text{3) } \text{MeMgBr, } \text{CdCl}_2 \end{matrix}} \text{Q} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{H}_3\text{O}^+]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{HCl} \\ \text{2) } \text{Mg/Et}_2\text{O} \\ \text{3) } \text{CO}_2 \text{ (dry ice)} \end{matrix}} \text{R}$$

The compound $\text{S}$ is:", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "An organic acid $\text{P}$ $(\text{C}_{11}\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_2)$ can easily be oxidized to a dibasic acid which reacts with ethylene glycol to produce a polymer Dacron. Upon ozonolysis, $\text{P}$ gives an aliphatic ketone as one of the products. $\text{P}$ undergoes the following reaction sequences to furnish $\text{R}$ via $\text{Q}$. The compound $\text{P}$ also undergoes another set of reactions to produce $\text{S}$.

$$\text{S} \xleftarrow[\text{5) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C}]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{NH}_3/\Delta \\ \text{3) } \text{Br}_2/\text{NaOH} \\ \text{4) } \text{CHCl}_3, \text{ KOH}, \Delta \end{matrix}} \text{P} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{NaBH}_4]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{H}_2/\text{Pd-C} \\ \text{2) } \text{SOCl}_2 \\ \text{3) } \text{MeMgBr, } \text{CdCl}_2 \end{matrix}} \text{Q} \xrightarrow[\text{4) } \text{H}_3\text{O}^+]{\begin{matrix} \text{1) } \text{HCl} \\ \text{2) } \text{Mg/Et}_2\text{O} \\ \text{3) } \text{CO}_2 \text{ (dry ice)} \end{matrix}} \text{R}$$

The compound $\text{R}$ is:", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "For a reaction, $\text{A} \rightleftharpoons \text{P}$, the plots of [A] and [P] with time at temperatures $T_1$ and $T_2$ are given below.

 and [P] at $T_1$ and $T_2$]

If $T_2 > T_1$, the correct statement(s) is (are) (Assume $\Delta H^\ominus$ and $\Delta S^\ominus$ are independent of temperature and ratio of $\ln K$ at $T_1$ to $\ln K$ at $T_2$ is greater than $T_2/T_1$. Here $H, S, G$ and $K$ are enthalpy, entropy, Gibbs energy and equilibrium constant, respectively.)", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1d13XhJmGOsccmRQm-FICMzy6wjZjwpKV=w1200"}

{"text": "Define the collections $\{E_1, E_2, E_3, ...\}$ of ellipses and $\{R_1, R_2, R_3...\}$ of rectangles as follows :
$E_1: \frac{x^2}{9} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1$;
$R_1$ : rectangle of largest area, with sides parallel to the axes, inscribed in $E_1$;
$E_n$ : ellipse $\frac{x^2}{a_n^2} + \frac{y^2}{b_n^2} = 1$ of the largest area inscribed in $R_{n-1}, n > 1$;
$R_n$ : rectangle of largest area, with sides parallel to the axes, inscribed in $E_n, n > 1$.
Then which of the following options is/are correct?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Let $f : \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$ be given by
\[ f(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
x^5 + 5x^4 + 10x^3 + 10x^2 + 3x + 1, & x < 0; \\
x^2 - x + 1, & 0 \le x < 1; \\
\frac{2}{3}x^3 - 4x^2 + 7x - \frac{8}{3}, & 1 \le x < 3; \\
(x - 2)\log_e(x - 2) - x + \frac{10}{3}, & x \ge 3;
\end{array} \right. \]
Then which of the following options is/are correct?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Consider the following reactions (unbalanced).
$$Zn + \text{Hot conc. } H_2SO_4 \mathrel{\mathop{\kern0pt\longrightarrow}
\limits_{}} G + R + X$$
$$Zn + \text{conc. } NaOH \mathrel{\mathop{\kern0pt\longrightarrow}
\limits_{}} T + Q$$
$$G + H_2S + NH_4OH \mathrel{\mathop{\kern0pt\longrightarrow}
\limits_{}} Z \,(\text{a precipitate}) + X + Y$$
Choose the correct option(s).", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "In a thermodynamic process on an ideal monatomic gas, the infinitesimal heat absorbed by the gas is given by $T dX$, where $T$ is temperature and $dX$ is the infinitesimal change in a thermodynamic quantity $X$. For a mole of monatomic ideal gas $X = \frac{3}{2} R \ln\left(\frac{T}{T_A}\right) + R \ln\left(\frac{V}{V_A}\right)$, where $R$ is the gas constant, $V$ is volume, and $T_A, V_A$ are constants. The process is carried out as shown in the $PV$-diagram with $P_0V_0 = \frac{1}{3} RT_0$. Match List-I with List-II:

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{List-I}} & & \pmb{\text{List-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Work done by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(P)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \ln 2 \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Change in internal energy in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(Q)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(R)} & RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 & \text{(S)} & \frac{4}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 (3 + \ln 2) \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \frac{5}{6} RT_0 \\ \hline \end{array}$$

If the process on one mole of monatomic ideal gas is as shown in the TV-diagram with $P_0V_0 = \frac{1}{3} RT_0$, the correct match for the quantities in List-I and List-II is:", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/1jSWKDW38ALjJvaKV-qL27YfNK2e0t9bs=w1200"}

{"text": "A musical instrument is made using four different metal strings: 1, 2, 3 and 4 with mass per unit length $\mu, 2\mu, 3\mu$ and $4\mu$ respectively. The instrument is played by vibrating the strings by varying the free length in the range $L_0$ to $2L_0$. It is found that for string-1 with mass per unit length $\mu$, free length $L_0$ and tension $T_0$, the fundamental mode frequency is $f_0$. 

If the tension in each string is $T_0$, identify the correct match for the highest fundamental frequency (in $f_0$ units) for each string.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|} \hline \textbf{List-I (Strings)} & \textbf{List-II (Highest Fundamental Frequency)} \\ \hline \text{I. String 1} & \text{P. } f_0 \\ \text{II. String 2} & \text{Q. } f_0/2 \\ \text{III. String 3} & \text{R. } f_0/\sqrt{2} \\ \text{IV. String 4} & \text{S. } f_0/\sqrt{3} \\ & \text{T. } f_0/\sqrt{6} \\ \hline \end{array}$$", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "In a thermodynamic process on an ideal monatomic gas, the infinitesimal heat absorbed by the gas is given by $T dX$, where $T$ is temperature and $dX$ is the infinitesimal change in a thermodynamic quantity $X$. For a mole of monatomic ideal gas $X = \frac{3}{2} R \ln\left(\frac{T}{T_A}\right) + R \ln\left(\frac{V}{V_A}\right)$, where $R$ is the gas constant, $V$ is volume, and $T_A, V_A$ are constants. The process is carried out as shown in the $PV$-diagram with $P_0V_0 = \frac{1}{3} RT_0$. Match List-I with List-II:

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{List-I}} & & \pmb{\text{List-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Work done by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(P)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \ln 2 \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Change in internal energy in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(Q)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 \to 3 & \text{(R)} & RT_0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Heat absorbed by the system in } 1 \to 2 & \text{(S)} & \frac{4}{3} RT_0 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \frac{1}{3} RT_0 (3 + \ln 2) \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \frac{5}{6} RT_0 \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Choose the correct match:", "image_url": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/d/12toe16FP2CY4siNLuXVbdwLo7eIefy9w=w1200"}

{"text": "Consider the Bohr's model of a one-electron atom where the electron moves around the nucleus. In the following, List-I contains some quantities for the $n^{\text{th}}$ orbit of the atom and List-II contains options showing how they depend on $n$.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{LIST-I}} & & \pmb{\text{LIST-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Radius of the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(P)} & \propto n^{-2} \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Angular momentum of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(Q)} & \propto n^{-1} \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Kinetic energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(R)} & \propto n^0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Potential energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(S)} & \propto n^1 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \propto n^2 \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \propto n^{1/2} \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Which of the following options has the correct combination considering List-I and List-II?", "image_url": ""}

{"text": "Consider the Bohr's model of a one-electron atom where the electron moves around the nucleus. In the following, List-I contains some quantities for the $n^{\text{th}}$ orbit of the atom and List-II contains options showing how they depend on $n$.

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|l|l|} \hline \pmb{\text{LIST-I}} & & \pmb{\text{LIST-II}} & \\ \hline \text{(I)} & \text{Radius of the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(P)} & \propto n^{-2} \\ \hline \text{(II)} & \text{Angular momentum of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(Q)} & \propto n^{-1} \\ \hline \text{(III)} & \text{Kinetic energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(R)} & \propto n^0 \\ \hline \text{(IV)} & \text{Potential energy of the electron in the } n^{\text{th}} \text{ orbit} & \text{(S)} & \propto n^1 \\ \hline & & \text{(T)} & \propto n^2 \\ \hline & & \text{(U)} & \propto n^{1/2} \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Which of the following options has the correct combination considering List-I and List-II?", "image_url": ""}
